############################################################ # PG Setup Code ############################################################ Context("IntegerFunctions");
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Let [`S = \{1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6\}`] a. How many subsets are there of cardinality 4?
[@KeyboardInstructions('[_]{C(6,4)}{5} (Note: you can enter "C(n,k)" for [`\binom{n}{k}\text{.}`])')@]**
a. How many subsets of cardinality 4 have [`\{2,3,5\}`] as a subset?
[_]{C(3,1)}{5}
a. How many subsets of cardinality 4 contain at least one odd number?
[_]{C(6,4)}{5}
a. How many subsets of cardinality 4 contain exactly one even number?
[_]{C(3,1)}{5}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION a. [`{6\choose 4} = 15`] subsets. a. [`{3 \choose 1} = 3`] subsets. We need to select 1 of the 3 remaining elements to be in the subset. a. [`{6 \choose 4} = 15`] subsets. All subsets of cardinality 4 must contain at least one odd number. a. [`{3 \choose 1} = 3`] subsets. Select 1 of the 3 even numbers. The remaining three odd numbers of [`S`] must all be in the set.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
