BEGIN_PGML You have 9 presents to give to your 4 kids. How many ways can this be done if: a. The presents are identical, and each kid gets at least one present?
[_]{$ans1}{5}
a. The presents are identical, and some kids might get no presents?
[_]{$ans2}{5}
a. The presents are unique, and some kids might get no presents?
[_]{$ans3}{5}
a. The presents are unique and each kid gets at least one present?
[_]{$ans4}{15}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION a. [`{8 \choose 5}`] ways, after giving one present to each kid, you are left with 5 presents (stars) which need to be divide among the 4 kids (giving 3 bars). a. [`{12 \choose 9}`] ways. You have 9 stars and 3 bars. a. [`4^9\text{.}`] You have 4 choices for whom to give each present. This is like making a function from the set of presents to the set of kids. a. [`4^9 - \left[{4 \choose 1}3^9 - {4\choose 2}2^9 + {4 \choose 3}1^9 \right]`] ways. Now the function from the set of presents to the set of kids must be surjective.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
