############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Recall, by [`8`]-bit strings, we mean strings of binary digits, of length 8. a. How many [`8`]-bit strings are there total?
[_]{$ans1}{5}
a. How many [`8`]-bit strings have weight 5?
[_]{$ans2}{5}
a. How many subsets of the set [`\{a,b,c,d,e,f,g,h\}`] contain exactly 5 elements?
[_]{$ans2}{5}
a. Explain why your answers to parts (b) and (c) are the same. Why are these questions equivalent?
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION a. [`2^8`] strings.
a. [`{8 \choose 5}`] strings.
a. [`{8 \choose 5}`] strings.
a. There is a bijection between subsets and bit strings: a 1 means that element in is the subset, a 0 means that element is not in the subset. To get a subset of an 8 element set we have an 8-bit string. To make sure the subset contains exactly 5 elements, there must be 5 1's, so the weight must be 5.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
############################################################ # End Problem ############################################################
